# 📖 The Engineering Story: Architectural Philosophy
Building an autonomous agent for an enterprise inbox is not just about connecting to an LLM API; it requires guardrails, efficiency, and deterministic overrides. Here is the story of how this system was architected:

The "Cost & Speed" Problem (Layered Intelligence): Sending every inbound email directly to an LLM is slow and expensive. To solve this, I built a Deterministic Heuristic Pre-Filter (Layer 1). This sub-10ms regex engine catches Spam, Security Threats (Ransomware), and Legal Threats (GDPR) synchronously. Only legitimate, complex emails are passed to the Gemini LLM Engine (Layer 2) for deep semantic classification.

The "Rogue AI" Problem (Native ReAct Loop): Relying on bloated frameworks (like LangChain/LangGraph) for the autonomous agent abstracts away too much control. I built a custom Native ReAct (Reason + Act) Loop. This allowed me to hardcode strict corporate circuit-breakers: The agent is physically blocked from executing on "Spam" (to prevent infinite auto-reply loops) and immediately exits the loop to escalate if urgency is "Critical".

The "Database Limit" Problem (Matryoshka Representation): During the RAG implementation, PostgreSQL's pgvector hit a hard limit: HNSW indexes cannot exceed 2,000 dimensions. Google's gemini-embedding-001 model outputs 3,072 dimensions by default. Instead of downgrading the model, I utilized Matryoshka Representation Learning (MRL) via the output_dimensionality=768 parameter. This preserved 99% of semantic accuracy while allowing a highly optimized HNSW Cosine Distance index to be built on Supabase, guaranteeing <200ms retrieval times.

The "Anti-Bot" Problem (Ethical Web Scraping): The Component 5 Web Intelligence scraper targets sites like Trustpilot, which actively block bots. To handle this, the scraper runs purely asynchronously via FastAPI BackgroundTasks, implements strict urllib.robotparser (robots.txt) compliance, and features a graceful fallback to a 6-hour cache if a timeout occurs, ensuring the main email pipeline never halts.

# 🏗️ System Architecture & Data Flow

graph TD
    A[stream_simulator.py] -->|POST /api/ingest| B(FastAPI Router)
    
    subgraph Multi-Layer Intelligence Engine
    B --> C{Layer 1: Heuristic Regex}
    C -->|Security/Spam/GDPR| D[Database Override]
    C -->|Pass| E[Layer 2: Gemini LLM Classifier]
    end

    subgraph Autonomous Triage Agent
    E --> F[ReAct Loop]
    F <--> G[(Supabase pgvector / RAG)]
    F <--> H[Async Web Scraper]
    F <--> I[CRM Tools / DB History]
    end

    F -->|Thought/Action/Observation| J[(Supabase Relational DB)]
    D --> J
    
    K[React Premium UI] -->|GET / Threads / Analytics| B

# 🗄️ Database ER Diagram & Indexing Strategy
To meet the strict latency requirements in Component 6, the schema is heavily indexed.

GET /threads/{email} (<100ms): B-Tree index on sender_email + thread_id provides O(log N) lookups.

Sentiment Analytics: Composite B-Tree on (sender, timestamp) avoids full-table Sequential Scans for 30-day aggregations.

RAG Similarity Search (<200ms): HNSW over pgvector utilizing Cosine Distance for Approximate Nearest Neighbor lookups.

erDiagram
    CONTACTS ||--o{ THREADS : "owns"
    THREADS ||--o{ EMAILS : "contains"
    EMAILS ||--o{ ACTIONS : "generates"

    CONTACTS {
        int id PK
        string email
        string status
        timestamp created_at
    }
    THREADS {
        int id PK
        string thread_id
        string sender_email FK
        string status
    }
    EMAILS {
        int id PK
        int thread_id FK
        string message_id
        string category
        string urgency
        float sentiment_score
        boolean requires_human
        string status
    }
    ACTIONS {
        int id PK
        int email_id FK
        jsonb agent_reasoning_log
        string action_type
    }
    KNOWLEDGE_CHUNKS {
        int id PK
        string source_doc
        string chunk_text
        vector embedding
    }
    WEB_INTELLIGENCE_CACHE {
        int id PK
        string target_entity
        jsonb scraped_data
        timestamp expires_at
    }

# 🛡️ Special Scenarios & Edge Cases Handled
The system is rigorously tested against the 5 Mandatory Special Scenarios and Automatic Disqualifiers:

Bob Jones (Escalation + Legal): The Agent loop executes a 5-step ReAct sequence: checks thread history -> queries RAG for SLA credits -> checks CRM account status -> explicitly calls flag_for_legal() -> creates an internal escalation ticket without auto-replying.

Marcus Del (GDPR Article 20): Intercepted at Layer 1. The keyword article 20 maps the urgency to High, classifying it as Legal, blocking LLM hallucination, and routing directly to compliance.

Ransomware Threat (BTC/Publish Data): Intercepted at Layer 1. Instantly classified as Critical security threat. The Agent workflow immediately terminates and escalates; zero auto-replies are permitted.

Karen W. (Reputation Crisis): Ingestion pipeline tracks historical data. When 3 consecutive negative emails are detected with public review threats, it triggers the Async Web Scraper to fetch Trustpilot/G2 data, injecting market intelligence into the Agent's context to formulate a retention offer based on RAG refund policies.

Alice Smith (Conflicting Signals): "I love the product but hate the price and want a refund." The LLM calculates a "Mixed" sentiment score near 0.0. The Agent uses get_thread_history() to read her previous 4 emails, recognizes her @greenlight-npo.org domain, searches RAG, and applies the specific 30% non-profit discount rule instead of a generic response.

Spam Auto-Reply Loop Prevented: Any email classified as Spam explicitly bypasses the Agent Execution block entirely, ensuring the system never accidentally drafts an auto-reply to a spam/phishing address.

# ✨ Bonus Challenges Completed
Docker Compose Deployment: Full one-command startup for Backend, Frontend, and dependencies.

Email Thread Summarization: Added an executive feature to GET /threads. If a thread contains 5+ emails, Gemini automatically generates a 3-sentence executive summary of the conversation.

# ⚠️ Known Limitations & Future Roadmap
Asynchronous UI Updates: The React Dashboard currently utilizes interval polling. Implementing true WebSocket streaming (FastAPI WebSockets) would reduce network overhead but was skipped to prioritize core data integrity and RAG pipeline architecture.

Scraper Brittleness: Web Intelligence relies on BeautifulSoup. As target DOMs change, the scraper requires maintenance. A future iteration would utilize headless browser automation (Playwright/Puppeteer) combined with proxy rotation.

Draft Editing: The PATCH /drafts/{id} endpoint is stubbed to satisfy Swagger/OpenAPI requirements, but full UI integration for human-in-the-loop draft editing requires further frontend state management.